          "title": "Electrochemical Disulfide Cleavage Using Carbon Fiber as Electrode",
          "what_it_is": "Design thermoset with disulfide crosslinks at 20-40% of crosslink sites (remainder permanent for creep resistance). For recycling, immerse composite in electrolyte (Na2SO4 or NaCl solution) and apply reducing potential (-0.5 to -1.0V vs. Ag/AgCl) using the carbon fiber itself as working electrode. Disulfides reduce to thiols, cleaving crosslinks and fragmenting the matrix.\n\nThe carbon fiber's high conductivity (~10^5 S/m axial) ensures uniform potential distribution. The recycling trigger is completely orthogonal—no temperature, pH, or solvent can accidentally trigger electrochemical reduction. This converts carbon fiber's conductivity from a liability (galvanic corrosion, lightning strike concerns) into an asset.",
          "when_to_elevate": "If electrolyte penetration can be achieved through matrix design (hydrophilic channels, swellable domains) or pre-treatment. Also if disulfide creep can be managed through hybrid crosslink approach (20-30% disulfide, 70-80% permanent).",
