          "title": "Toughened Polybenzoxazine with Acid-Cleavable Mannich Bridges",
          "what_it_is": "Polybenzoxazines achieve Tg >250°C through ring-opening polymerization of benzoxazine monomers, forming a network of phenolic-amine Mannich base linkages. These Mannich bridges are known to be acid-labile in small-molecule chemistry—protonation of the tertiary amine converts it to a leaving group, enabling hydrolysis. For composites, toughening with 10-15 wt% core-shell rubber particles or 15-20 wt% high-Tg thermoplastic (PES, PEI) addresses the historical brittleness limitation.\n\nRecycling would use dilute acid (0.1-1M HCl or acetic acid) at 80-120°C to cleave Mannich bridges and fragment the network. Commercial benzoxazine monomers are available from Huntsman, and bio-based versions from cashew nut shell liquid (cardanol) provide a sustainability angle.",
