          "title": "Vinylogous Urethane Vitrimer with Locked Catalyst",
          "what_it_is": "Adopt Mallinda-type vinylogous urethane chemistry which has demonstrated Tg up to 200°C in aerospace qualification programs. Address the creep concern through catalyst encapsulation: embed exchange catalyst in thermally-activated microcapsules (polyimide or fluoropolymer shells, Tm 200-220°C) that only release above service temperature.\n\nDuring service at T <180°C, capsules remain intact and exchange is suppressed—the network behaves as a conventional thermoset with no measurable creep. For recycling, heat above 220°C to rupture capsules and release catalyst, enabling thermoforming or reprocessing. This decouples the topology freezing temperature (Tv) from Tg through kinetic control rather than thermodynamic design.",
          "when_to_use_instead": "If chemical recycling (glycolysis, acid dissolution) is undesirable due to solvent handling or infrastructure requirements. Preferred for applications where composite reshaping (vs. fiber recovery) is valuable.",
          "why_it_works": "Vinylogous urethane exchange proceeds through transamination, catalyzed by free amine or Lewis acid. Without catalyst, activation energy is ~100 kJ/mol and exchange half-life at 180°C is years. With catalyst, activation energy drops to ~60 kJ/mol and exchange occurs in minutes. Encapsulating catalyst shifts the effective Tv above the capsule melting point."
